This exercise teaches about:
modules, importation and usage.
time module
f-strings and format codes.

You can learn about what is availabel inside the module reading doc strings
with this code:

import time
data = [x for x in dir(time) if not x.startswith('_')]
for e in data:
    func = getattr(time, e)
    doc = getattr(func, '__doc__', 'No Docstring')
    print(f'---------------------------{e}-----------------------------------')
    print(doc)
    print() 

There is an online web that documents modules in the standard library.

https://docs.python.org/3/library/index.html
https://docs.python.org/3/library/time.html

The standard library is the collection of modules that comes pre-installed with
Python — no pip install needed. 

There are around 200+ modules included.
Some of the most common ones, grouped by purpose:
Data & math — math, decimal, fractions, random, statistics, collections, itertools, functools
Text & strings — string, re (regex), textwrap, unicodedata
Files & OS — os, sys, pathlib, shutil, glob, tempfile
Date & time — time, datetime, calendar
I/O & formats — json, csv, xml, html, sqlite3, zipfile, gzip
Networking — http, urllib, socket, email, smtplib
Dev tools — logging, unittest, pdb, argparse, typing, inspect

Beyond the standard library, there are third-party libraries that you install 
with pip. 

These are what make Python's ecosystem so powerful:
Data science — numpy, pandas, matplotlib, scipy
Web development — django, flask, fastapi
Machine learning — scikit-learn, tensorflow, pytorch
Automation & scraping — requests, beautifulsoup4, selenium
Image processing — pillow, opencv-python

All of these live on PyPI (Python Package Index, at pypi.org), which hosts overi
500,000 packages. 
When you run pip install pandas, pip downloads it from there.

The key distinction: 
standard library is "batteries included" with Python, 
third-party libraries are community-built tools you add as needed.


An f-string is a string literal prefixed with f that lets you embed Python 
expressions directly inside curly braces {}, which get evaluated at runtime:

f"Seconds since Jan 1, 1970: {now:,.4f} or {now:.2e} in scientific notation")

Documentation about format codes can be found at 
https://docs.python.org/3/library/string.html#format-specification-mini-language

If you know C printf, you will feel confortable.
